{"cursor":"29536","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n{{Infobox ethnic group |image = |caption=Two RarÃ¡muri women (one with a baby\nnursing) at Arareco Lake near Creel, Chihuahua, Mexico. The Tarahumara women\nwear the traditional brightly colored clothes for which they are famous. These\nwomen make and sell hand-made items at the lake. |group=Tarahumara 'RarÃ¡muri' |poptime=Mexico:approx Irigoyen and Palma. RarajÃ­pari, the Tarahumara Indian Kick-\nball Race. La Prensa. Chihuahua 1995. Kindle edition 2012 In their\nlanguage, the term 'rarÃ¡muri' refers specifically to the men, women are referred\nto as 'mukÃ­' (individually) and as 'omugÃ­' or 'igÃ³male' (collectively).\n\nOriginally inhabitants of much of the state of Chihuahua, the RarÃ¡muri retreated\nto the high sierras and canyons such as the Copper Canyon in the Sierra Madre\nOccidental on the arrival of Spanish explorers in the 16th century. the Tarahumar of Mexico, their environment and\nmaterial culture. Universuty of Utah Press, 1963. The area of the Sierra\nMadre Occidental which they now inhabit is often called the Sierra Tarahumara\nbecause of their presence.\n\nCurrent estimates put the population of the RarÃ¡muri in 2006 at between 50,000\nand 70,000 people. Most still practice a traditional lifestyle, inhabiting\nnatural shelters such as caves or cliff overhangs, as well as small cabins of\nwood or stone. Staple crops are corn and beans; however, many of the RarÃ¡muri\nstill practice transhumance, raising cattle, sheep, and goats. Almost all\nRarÃ¡muri migrate in some form or another in the course of the year.\n\nThe Tarahumara language belongs to the Uto-Aztecan family. Although it is in\ndecline under pressure from Spanish, it is still widely spoken.\n","linknr":361,"url":"Tarahumara","recorded":1375085621,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Tarahumara_people&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Tarahumara_people&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_d